        <head xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-Hd1e109">CAP. IV</head>
        <head xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-Hd1e112" type="question-title">
          What kind of utility does the baptism of John have</head>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-d1e115"> 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-Qd1e117">
              Therefore for what reason was the baptism of John useful?
              Because men were prepared for the baptism of Christ by the use of the one baptizing.
            </quote>
            <!-- unclear if this should be a quote or a copyOf section -->
            <bibl>Hugo, De Sacramentis, XXX</bibl>
          </cit>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-d1e121">
          But, why is the baptism of John spoken of 
          the way that the Truth speaks:
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d2c4-Qd1e125" ana="#mt21_25">From where did the baptism of John come?</quote>
            <bibl>Matthew 21:25</bibl>
          </cit> 
          Because in this case the visible operation of John 
          was of one washing externally, 
          not the invisible grace of God 
          who is operating internally.
          But nevertheless this operation of John 
          was from God, 
          and the baptism was from God, 
          not from man; 
          but it was said of man, 
          because nothing was done there 
          that a man did not do.
        </p>
      </div>
